teen essays that collectively advance a discussion about sexual politics, media, technology, and globalization. Covering the internet, television, books, telecommunications, newspapers, and activist media work, the volume directs focused attention to the ways in which gender and sexuality issues are constructed and mobilized across the globe. Contributors’ essays span diverse global sites from Myanmar and Morocco to the Balkans, France, U.S., and China, and cover an extensive terrain from consumption, aesthetics and whiteness to masculinity, transnational labor, and cultural citizenship. Circuits of Visibility initiates a necessary conversation and political critique about the mediated global terrain on which sexuality is defined, performed, regulated, made visible, and experienced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFeminism and mass media. 0aMass media and culture. 0aMass media and globalization. 0aSex role and globalization. 0aSex role in mass media. 0aWomen in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aAl-Qasimi, Noor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuvall, Spring-Serenity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchchaibi, Nabil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErjavec, Karmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegde, Radha S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoallem, Minoo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoorti, Sujata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOssman, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadios, Jan Maghinay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParameswaran, Radhika, econt